@NODE install "Installation"


 1. Installation


 This is the Aminet Release of the @{b}FIR Filter Designer V2.3@{ub}.
 Install  the   @{b}FIR Filter Designer V2.3@{ub}  using  the  script
 located in this directory.

 AmigaOS 3.x or up is  required. A fast processor  and a GFX
 card are recommended but not mandatory.

 If your  system  still runs  AmigaOS 2.x, you  can  use the
 @{b}FIR Filter Designer V1.2@{ub}  which  is  available   on  Aminet.

@ENDNODE


@NODE filters "Finite Impulse Response Filters"


 2. Finite Impulse Response Filters


 The N tap  FIR filter consists of N-1 delayers,  N multiplyers,  each
 with its correspondant values a(j), and N-1 adders, or a global adder.

 The abbreviation FIR stands for Finite Impulse Response.  Such is the
 characteristic of the impulse response of FIR filters. Because of the
 non-recurse filter structure,  it is finite in duration.  Actually it
 has a duration of N, where N is the number of taps of the filter.

  @{FG shine}@{@FG text}

     x(k) ------>[T]------->[T]--- - - - - ----->[T]-----
             |         |         |          |           |
            [*] a(0)  [*] a(1)  [*] a(2)   [*] a(N-2)  [*] a(N-1)
             |         |         |          |           |
             |         v         v          v           v
             -------->[+]------>[+]- - - ->[+]-------->[+]----> y(k)

  @{FG text}@{@FG text}

             @{b}FIR Filter Elements:@{ub}

             Delayer:     x(k)-->@{FG shine}@{@FG text}[T]@{FG text}@{@FG text}-->y(k)      y(k) = x(k-1)

                                a(j)
             Multiplyer:  x(k)-->@{FG shine}@{@FG text}[*]@{FG text}@{@FG text}-->y(k)      y(k) = a(j) * x(k)

                                z(k)
                                  |
                                  v
             Adder:       x(k)-->@{FG shine}@{@FG text}[+]@{FG text}@{@FG text}-->y(k)      y(k) = x(k) + z(k)



 The output sequence  y(k) is calculated by a convolution of the input
 sequence x(k) with the impulse response a(j) of the FIR filter:

 @{FG shine}@{@FG text}
                         N-1
                         ___
                         \\
                 y(k) =  /  x(k-j) * a(j)
                         ---
                         j=0
 @{FG text}@{@FG text}

 One noticeable  feature of  FIR  filters in  general is their  linear
 phase,  because  the  delay is  equal  for all  frequencies.  This is
 especially important in video technology.

@ENDNODE


@NODE purpose "Filter Design"


 3. Filter Design

 
 The  problem  of  designing  finite  impulse  response (FIR)  digital
 filters experienced  great  activity in  the  early  1970`s.  Most of
 this  work was  directed at the  problem  of  optimal  filter  design,
 in the weighted  Chebyshev sense.  One  algorithm  for  this  program,
 by McClellan, Parks  and  Rabiner, will design the optimal  Chebyshev
 approximation  for  linear  phase filters. The Chebyshev optimization
 is  done  very  efficiently by means of the  Remez exchange algorithm,
 and  this  particular  FIR filter design  program has found  wide use.

 The filter design process is always a compromise  among filter length,
 transition width and passband / stopband  deviation  (in the bandpass 
 case). Not all of these  specifications  can be  choosen  arbitrarily.

 The @{"window method" LINK wfirdesign}  filter design process is based upon Fourier series.
 It is possible to represent a  frequency function as a Fourier series,
 whose coefficients represent the coefficients of the filter.

 To form a casual filter, the  Fourier series is truncated and shifted.
 Truncating the Fourier series  causes a phenomenon  called the "Gibbs
 effect" - a spike  occurs  wherever  there is a  discontinuity in the
 desired  magnitude of the filter.  To  counteract  this,  the  filter
 coefficients are convolved in the  frequency domain with the spectrum
 of a window function,  thus  smoothing  the edge  transitions  at any
 discontinuity. This convolution in the frequency domain is equivalent
 to multiplying the  filter coefficients  with the window coefficients
 in the time domain.

 The window design  method starts  with a very long  series, in theory
 infinite,  that is  truncated  to the  desired  length.  Coefficients
 beyond the  truncation are  simply  ignored.  The window removes even
 more information.  The equiripple method  optimizes the  series for a
 given number of coefficients.

 The method first  programmed by Parks and  McClellan in FORTRAN, uses
 an  optimization  algorithm  called  the  @{"Remez" LINK firdesign}  exchange  algorithm.
 Instead of  describing the coefficients by a Fourier series, they are
 described using  a  polynomial  series.  This  design  method  allows
 sharper transitions with better  stopband attenuation than the window
 method, but there is a ripple in  the  passband.  This  Remez type of
 design normally produces equiripple filters, where the ripples in the
 passbands  and  stopbands  are of  equal height within  any one  band.

 The Remez algorithm also demands  very  high numerical  precision, so
 the  @{b}FIR Filter Designer V2.3@{ub}  uses   64-bit  double  math  precision
 arithmetic for  all calculations.  If you switch on the  DEBUG option
 via  the  respective @{"tooltype" LINK tooltypes}, the  math errors  during optimization
 are  reported  by  the program.  Note that the  design may  still  be
 correct but  check the  magnitude  carefully in these cases. Normally
 the  DEBUG  option should  be  switched  off, in  order  to  increase
 optimization speed.


@ENDNODE


@NODE firdesign "Remez FIR filter design"


 4. Remez FIR filter design


 Select the  filter   parameters  or  load  a  filter  specification
 file  (#?.FIR).  Click on the  design button  and  wait  until  the
 filter is designed.  This can take  up to  some  minutes if you use 
 a standard Amiga and many filter taps (> 32).

 Note  that standard  FIR  filters  should  not have more than about 
 64 taps.  This  program however  supports a filter length up to 512 
 taps (in the registered version). 

 In many cases, the result  of  the  design of higher degree filters  
 (>64 taps) produces wrong data.  Be aware of that numerical problem,
 due  to limited  math  precision,  and  verify  your filter  design.

 If the Remez equiripple design  method fails to meet specifications,
 the gain will typically exceed  1.0  even though this was specified
 as the maximum gain. Common causes for design failures are:
     * too narrow transition bands
     * very narrow passbands
     * very narrow stopbands
     * non-symmetric pass and stopbands

 If you  are  experienced  in  designing digital  FIR filters, these 
 long  filters are an option for very high precise FIR filters, with 
 attenuation of more than -150 dB.

 The resulting  filter  parameters  will  be stored in an ASCII-file.
 The name and the path  of this file can be specified by a @{"tooltype" LINK tooltypes}
 of the program.

 Please use one of the standard text viewers to  have a look at this 
 log file.

 If  you select  invalid filter  parameters, the program will pop up
 a requester which gives detailed information about the problem.



 @{b}Parameter Description@{ub}


 Filter-Type:    Bandpass
                 Differentiator
                 Hilbert Transformator

 Filter-Length:  3 to 128 (512 in the registered version).

 Grid-Density:   2 to 32 (internal optimization value).

 Bitwidth:       0 to 16 (32 in the registered version).
                 The filter taps are scaled with 2^bitwidth.
                 A value of 0 means no scaling (floating point).

 Bands:          1 to 10 (number of the defined bands).

 From:           Lower frequency of the specified Band.

 To:             Upper frequency of the specified Band.

 Value:          0.0 to 1.0 (you can also use higher values than 1.0)
                 0.0 means stopband
                 1.0 means passband

 Weight:         Weight for optimization. This value defines  how hard the
                 program tries to meet the value for the  respective band.

                 Note  that  the  frequency  value  is   relative  to  the 
                 sampling  frequency.  Load  @{"example" LINK firexample}  files  (#?.FIR) for
                 better  understanding.  The  bands  have to  be sorted in 
                 ascending order.

                 The  value for  grid is  needed  only  for  the  internal
                 optimization algorithm. Usually, the value 16 is best for 
                 all purposes, but you can "play" with this value to get a 
                 better result.
@ENDNODE


@NODE wfirdesign "Window method FIR filter design"


 5. Window method FIR filter design


 Select the  filter   parameters  or  load  a  filter  specification
 file  (#?.WFIR).  Click on the  design button  and  wait  until  the
 filter is designed.  This can take  up to  some  minutes if you use
 a standard Amiga and many filter taps (> 64).

 Note  that standard  FIR  filters  should  not have more than about
 128 taps.  This  program however supports a filter length up to 512
 taps (in the registered version). Increasing the filter length does
 not affect the ripple, but narrows the transition width.

 If you  are  experienced  in  designing digital  FIR filters, these
 long  filters are an option for very high precise FIR filters, with
 attenuation of more than -150 dB.

 The resulting  filter  parameters  will  be stored in an ASCII-file.
 The name and the path  of this file can be specified by a @{"tooltype" LINK tooltypes}
 of the program.

 Please use one of the standard text viewers to  have a look at this
 log file.

 If  you select  invalid filter  parameters, the program will pop up
 a requester which gives detailed information about the problem.



 @{b}Parameter Description@{ub}


 Filter-Type:    Lowpass
                 Highpass
                 Bandpass
                 Bandstop

 Filter-Length:  3 to 128 (512 in the registered version)

 Window-Type:    Rectangle
                 Triangular
                 Hamming (alpha = 0.54)
                 Generalized Hamming
                 Hanning
                 Kaiser
                 Chebyshev

 Bitwidth:       0 to 16 (32 in the registered version).
                 The filter taps are scaled with 2^bitwidth.
                 A value of 0 means no scaling (floating point).

 Cut-off         Cut-off frequency of the filter.
 Frequency:      Used for Lowpass or Highpass filters.

 Low Frequency:  Low frequency edge of the filter.
                 Used for Bandpass or Bandstop filters.

 High Frequency: High frequency edge of the filter.
                 Used for Bandpass or Bandstop filters.

 Ripple:         Value in dB which specifies the desired ripple
                 of the passband. Used for Chebyshev window.

 Transition:     Transition width in Hz, normalized to the sampling
                 frequency. Used for Chebyshev window.

 Generalized     Parameter for the Generalized Hamming window.
 Hamming Alpha:  w(m) = alpha + (1-alpha) * cos((2pi*m)/(N-1))
                 where N is the length of the filter.

 Kaiser          Parameter of the Kaiser (i0-sinh) window.
 Attenuation:    The attenuation must be at least 20.96 dB.

                 Note  that  all  frequency  values  are  relative  to  the
                 sampling  frequency.  Load  @{"example" LINK wfirexample}  files  (#?.WFIR) for
                 better  understanding.

@ENDNODE


@NODE prism "Prism"


 6. Prism


 Prism is the program module that displays the previous
 designed filter in the frequency domain  (Global-Mode).

 @{b}Parameter Description@{ub}


 Global-Mode:       Frequency-Domain
                    Time-Domain
                    No Dimension

 Sample-Frequency:  >0.0 (0.5 for normalized display)

 Display 1:         Absolute        - sqrt (im^2 + re^2)
                    Phase           - atan (im / re)
                    Corrected Phase - atan (im / re) + x
                    Real            - re
                    Imaginary       - im
                    Nothing         - guess what ?

 Display 2:         Same as Display 1

 X-Axis:            X-Linear  (Min...Max)
                    X-Log     (Min...Max)

 Y1-Axis            Y1-Linear (Min...Max)
                    Y2-Log    (Min...Max)

 Y2-Axis            Same as Y1-Axis

                    Note  that if  Min and Max  are  both
                    0  for  the  Y-Axis, the  graph  will
                    be  autoscaled  by  the  program.  If
                    you resize the  Prism Data window  or
                    change the settings, click the Redraw
                    gadget to update the display.

                    Press  @{b}SPACE@{ub}  to invoke the @{"tooltype" LINK tooltypes}
                    defined  external viewer, in order to
                    view  the  log  file  for  the latest
                    design.

@ENDNODE


@NODE tooltypes "Tooltype settings"


 7. Tooltype settings

 
 BITWIDTH=x                 The filter taps are calculated with 2^x precision.
                            If x is set to 0, the taps are calculated as real
                            values. Allowed values are 0 to 16   (32  in  the
                            registered version).  The  slider  gadget of  the
                            program defaults to this value on startup.

 REFRESH=ON                 Data window is updated whenever there is a change
                            of the windowsize or gadget values.

 REFRESH=OFF                Data  window has  to be  refreshed manually. This
                            option is of particular use for slow systems.

 DEBUG=ON                   If a  math error occurs during  the  optimization,
                            the  program  gives  an  error  report.

 DEBUG=OFF                  No  error  report  to  be  generated.


 VERBOSE=ON                 The  program  tells  you  what  it currently does.

 VERBOSE=OFF                No  verbose  output.


 OUTPUT=T:FIRDesign.LOG     This is the  filename of  the log  file, which is
                            generated  during the  optimization. It shows the
                            calculated  filter  taps, the  parameters and the
                            deviation for the selected bands.


 VIEWER=MORE                Here you can select your  favourite  text  viewer.


 INVOKEVIEWER=ALWAYS        The viewer is always invoked when Prism starts up.

 INVOKEVIEWER=NEVER         The viewer is never invoked.

 INVOKEVIEWER=SPACE         The viewer is only invoked if you press the SPACE
                            bar,  while  using  Prism.

 FONTNAME=XHelvetica.font   The name of the font that is used  throughout the
                            program.

 FONTSIZE=11                The size of the font (8...15).

@ENDNODE


@NODE future "Future Enhancements"


 8. Future Enhancements


 Future  enhancements to this  program are pretty  unlikely,
 due to significant  low response from  the Amiga community.


 Formerly planned enhancements include:

   * Prism can toggle between frequency and time domain.

   * Filtering of sound samples using an external program.

   * 1 dimensional and 2 dimensional filtering of pictures
     using an external program.

   * Support for the design of IIR filters.

   * More window types for the window design method.

   * Port the program to PPC Amiga.

   * The Filter @{"library" LINK library} is your task ...


 Feel free  to send  me  suggestions, bug reports and ideas.

@ENDNODE


@NODE copy "Copyright"


 9. Copyright
 

 This program is  @{b}SHAREWARE@{ub} !!!  Please  register  if you use
 it frequently.  You  will get a  @{b}keyfile@{ub}  that  enables  the
 program to  calculate filters up  to a  length of  512  taps.
 This  version  is  limited  to  128 taps,  which  should  be
 enough  for  normal   applications. The bitwidth scaling  of
 this version is limited to  16  bits whereas the  registered
 version  permits up  to  32  bits.  Moreover  the  numerical
 output for the filter taps is more precise in the registered 
 version and the annoying shareware requesters are suppressed.
 Use the  @{b}ORDERFORM@{ub}  to register.  Thank you for your support.


